of the Richard Pryor album cover, which I loved doing, I got two letters: One was a letter from the [[National Geographic Society]]’s attorneys offering to sue me for defaming their publication. The second letter was a [[1970 Grammy Awards|Grammy nomination]] for the best album cover."<ref>[http://garyburdenforrtwerk.com/2009/09/richard-pryor/ Richard Pryor | Gary Burden For R. Twerk & Co.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320021821/http://garyburdenforrtwerk.com/2009/09/richard-pryor/ |date=2018-03-20 }}.</ref> * [[The Rolling Stones]] – ''[[Some Girls]]'' (1978) ** The original pressing of the album featured an inner sleeve containing many black and white photos of both the band members as well as other celebrities, all strategically positioned to show through cut-out holes on the outer sleeve. After protests from some of the persons depicted, the inner sleeve was revised to replace the offending photos with color blocks and text reading ''Pardon Our Appearance'' and ''Cover Under (Re)Construction''. * [[Sonic Youth]] – ''[[Sister (Sonic Youth album)|Sister]]'' (1987) ** The album's artwork has been edited two separate times to obscure images; the first of which was a [[Richard Avedon]] image depicting a 12-year-old girl, due to a lawsuit threat. The other instance was when an image of the [[Disney]] [[Magic Kingdom]] was deliberately covered with a barcode, likely due to copyright complaints.<ref>[[Sister (Sonic Youth album)#Packaging]]</ref>{{Better source|reason=per WP:CIRCULAR|date=October 2015}} * [[Sufjan Stevens]] – ''[[Illinois (Sufjan Stevens album)|Illinois]]'' (2005) ** Shortly after the release of the album, reports arose that [[DC Comics]] had issued a [[cease and desist letter]] to Stevens' label [[Asthmatic Kitty]] because of the depiction of [[Superman]] on the cover.,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chicagoist.com/2005/07/05/not_so_fast_there_superman.php |title=Not So Fast There Superman |publisher=[[Chicagoist]] |date=July 5, 2005 |accessdate=April 2, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130417154126/http://chicagoist.com/2005/07/05/not_so_fast_there_superman.php |archivedate=April 17, 2013 |df= }}</ref> However, on October 4, 2005, Asthmatic Kitty announced that there had been no cease and desist letter; the record company's own lawyers had warned about the copyright infringement. On June 30, 2005, Asthmatic Kitty's distributor [[Secretly Canadian]] asked its retailers not to sell the album; however, it was not recalled. On July 5, the distributor told its retailers to go ahead and sell their copies,<ref name="Billboard">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/62152/stevens-album-soars-despite-superman-flap |title=Stevens Album Soars Despite 'Superman' Flap |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=July 8, 2005 |accessdate=June 17, 2010 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140930190848/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/62152/stevens-album-soars-despite-superman-flap |archivedate=September 30, 2014 |df= }}</ref> as DC Comics agreed to allow Asthmatic Kitty to sell the copies of the album that were already manufactured, but the image was removed from subsequent pressings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asthmatickitty.com/news.php?newsID=23 |title=A Statement From Asthmatic Kitty and DC Comics |publisher=[[Asthmatic Kitty]] |date=October 4, 2005 |accessdate=April 2, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100324063743/http://asthmatickitty.com/news.php?newsID=23 |archivedate=March 24, 2010 }}</ref> Soon after it was made public that the cover would be changed, copies of the album featuring Superman were sold for as high as $75 on [[eBay]].<ref name="Billboard"/> On the vinyl edition released on November 22, 2005, Superman's image is covered by a balloon sticker. The image of the balloon sticker was also used on the cover of the Compact Disc and later printings of the double vinyl release.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://asthmatickitty.com/illinois |title=Illinois |publisher=[[Asthmatic Kitty]] |accessdate=April 11, 2010 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100512161409/http://asthmatickitty.com/illinois |archivedate=May 12, 2010 |df= }}</ref> * [[Tad (band)|Tad]] – ''[[8-Way Santa]]'' (1991) ** The original cover featured a photograph of a man and woman which had been found in a thrift store. The couple on the album sued for unauthorized use of their image and the cover was replaced on later pressings.<ref name="stonelist"/> * [[U2]] – ''[[No Line on the Horizon]]'' (2009) ** The cover image, ''Boden Sea'' by [[Hiroshi Sugimoto]], had previously been used by [[Richard Chartier]] and [[Taylor Deupree]] for their 2006 album ''Specification.Fifteen''. Deupree called U2's cover "nearly an exact rip-off" and stated that for the band to obtain the rights to the image it was "simply a phone call and a check."<ref name="webcitation.org">https://www.webcitation.org/5kjDg3ppi?url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/member/member.html?mode=getarticle&file=fa20090320a1.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/u2/42195|title=U2 album artwork branded 'rip off' - NME|date=21 January 2009|publisher=|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kjDp0PjW?url=http://www.nme.com/news/u2/42195|archivedate=23 October 2009|df=}}</ref> Sugimoto refuted both of these claims, calling the use of the same photograph a coincidence and stating that no money was involved in the deal with U2.<ref name="webcitation.org"/> * [[Vampire Weekend]] – ''[[Contra (album)|Contra]]'' (2010) ** The cover art, taken in the 1980s, features a blond girl staring into the camera with an unidentifiable expression on her face. In July 2010, the band and their label were sued by the model, Kirsten Kennis. Kennis claimed photographer [[Tod Scott Brody]], who sold the image to the band, did not take the picture and she was not aware her image was being used until she saw the copy her teenage daughter had bought.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2010/07/15/vampire-weekend-contra-lawsuit/ |title=Vampire Weekend sued by 'Contra' cover model |author=Simon Vozick-Levinson |publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=15 July 2010 |accessdate=17 December 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119002856/http://music-mix.ew.com/2010/07/15/vampire-weekend-contra-lawsuit/ |archivedate=19 January 2012 |df= }}</ref> Vampire Weekend also sued Brody, arguing that he was liable for any damages in the Kennis case due to misrepresentation on his part.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bychawski|first1=Adam|title=Vampire Weekend issue lawsuit to 'Contra' photographer {{!}} NME.COM|url=http://www.nme.com/news/vampire-weekend/54077|website=NME.COM|accessdate=2 October 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101206044008/http://www.nme.com/news/vampire-weekend/54077|archivedate=6 December 2010|df=}}</ref> Kennis and Vampire Weekend amicably settled their lawsuit in August 2011.<ref name="p4kdrop">{{Cite web| last = Breihan| first = Tom| title = Vampire Weekend settle with cover model| publisher = [[Pitchfork Media]]| date = 2011-07-15| url = http://pitchfork.com/news/43537-vampire-weekend-settle-with-cover-model/| accessdate = 2011-09-05| deadurl = no| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110818013642/http://www.pitchfork.com/news/43537-vampire-weekend-settle-with-cover-model/| archivedate = 2011-08-18| df = }}</ref> However, the model and the band continued to pursue litigation against Brody.<ref name="p4kdrop"/> * [[The Velvet Underground]] – ''[[The Velvet Underground & Nico]]'' (1967) ** Shortly after its release, the band and their label [[Verve Records]] were threatened with a lawsuit by [[Warhol superstar]] [[Eric Emerson]], whose image is projected upside-down on the back cover of the album.<ref name="33 1/3">{{cite book |last=Harvard |first=Joe |title=The Velvet Underground and Nico |origyear=2004 |series=[[33⅓]] |year=2007 |publisher=[[Continuum International Publishing Group]] |location=New York, NY |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Af46S4wukzoC&printsec=frontcover&q |isbn=0-8264-1550-4}}</ref> Copies of the album were withdrawn from sale so the image could be censored by a large sticker.<ref name="33 1/3"/> The image was restored on the 1996 compact disc release of the album.
==Violence== <!--IMPORTANT! If you add an album without providing a reference or providing an explanation for why or how its album cover is "controversial", THE ALBUM WILL BE REMOVED! See discussion page.--> * [[The Beatles]] – ''[[Yesterday and Today]]'' (1966) ** In early 1966, photographer [[Robert Whitaker (photographer)|Robert Whitaker]] had the Beatles in the studio for a [[conceptual art]] piece titled ''A Somnambulant Adventure''. For the shoot, Whitaker took a series of pictures of the group dressed in butcher smocks and draped with pieces of meat and body parts from plastic baby dolls. The group played along as they were tired of the usual photo shoots—Lennon recalled the band having "boredom and resentment at having to do ''another'' photo session and ''another'' Beatles thing"<ref>{{cite book|last=Sheff|first=David|title=All We Are Saying: The Last Major Interview with John Lennon and Yoko Ono|year=2000|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=9780312254643|page=219}}</ref>—and the concept was compatible with their own black humour.<ref name="Anthology">The Beatles. (2000). ''[[The Beatles Anthology]]'', San Francisco, CA: Chronicle Books LLC. {{ISBN|0-8118-2684-8}}, 204–205</ref> Although not originally intended as an album cover, the Beatles submitted photographs from the session for their promotional materials. According to a 2002 interview published in ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'', former Capitol president [[Alan W. Livingston]] stated that it was [[Paul McCartney]] who pushed strongly for the photo's inclusion as the album cover, and that McCartney reportedly described it as "our comment on the [[Vietnam War|[Vietnam] war]]".<ref name="roadshow">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/roadshow/fts/jackpot_200302A14.html |title=Antiques Roadshow &#124; Follow the Stories &#124; The Beatles' "Butcher" Cover &#124; PBS |first=Dennis |last=Gaffney |date=27 October 2008 |work=PBS.org |accessdate=9 February 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110925034827/http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/roadshow/fts/jackpot_200302A14.html |archivedate=25 September 2011 |df= }}</ref> A photograph of the band smiling amid the mock carnage was used as promotional advertisements for the British release of the "[[Paperback Writer]]" single. In the United States, [[Capitol Records]] printed approximately 750,000 copies of ''Yesterday and Today'' with the same photograph as "Paperback Writer".<ref name="Schaffner2">[[Nicholas Schaffner|Schaffner, Nicholas]]. (1977). ''The Beatles Forever'', Harrisburg, PA: Cameron House. {{ISBN|0-8117-0225-1}}, 55</ref><ref name = "Billboard Jun 1966">{{cite magazine | title = Beatles' LP Makes Cap. Run for Cover |magazine= Billboard | volume = 78 | issue = 26 |pages=3, 6| publisher = Billboard Publishing | location = Cincinnati, Ohio | date = 25 June 1966 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=MikEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA3}}</ref> Reaction was immediate, as Capitol received complaints from some dealers. The record was immediately recalled under orders from Capitol parent company [[EMI]] chairman [[Sir Joseph Lockwood]]<ref name="rarebeatles.com">{{cite web |url=http://www.rarebeatles.com/album2/discog/pwhite.htm |title=Butcher cover, Canadian – Paul White Letter |publisher=Rarebeatles.com |date= |accessdate=18 August 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AhAnrx2N?url=http://www.rarebeatles.com/album2/discog/pwhite.htm |archivedate=15 September 2012 |df= }}</ref> and all copies were ordered shipped back to the record label, leading to its rarity and popularity among collectors. * [[Cannibal Corpse]] – Various albums (1990–2006) ** [[Death metal]] band Cannibal Corpse's albums were all banned from Germany until 2006 due to their graphic album covers and disturbing lyrics. The band was also forbidden to play any songs from those albums while touring in Germany. This prohibition was not lifted until June 2006. In an interview from 2004, George Fisher attempted to recall what originally provoked the ban: "A woman saw someone wearing one of our shirts, I think she is a schoolteacher, and she just caused this big stink about it. So [now] we can't play anything from the first three records. And it really sucks because kids come up and they want us to play all the old songs — and we would — but they know the deal. We can't play 'Born in a Casket' but can play 'Dismembered and Molested."<ref name=innerview>{{cite web|last=Falina|first=Melanie|title=Cannibal Corpse Just Wants to Sing About Ripping Apart Human Flesh in Peace|work=Chicago Innerview|publisher=Innerview Media, Inc|date=February 2004|url=http://www.chicagoinnerview.com/archives/feb04_cannibal_corpse.htm|accessdate=February 5, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090311003400/http://www.chicagoinnerview.com/archives/feb04_cannibal_corpse.htm|archivedate=March 11, 2009}}</ref><ref name=tombreview>{{cite web|last=Watson|first=Tyler|title=Reviews of Cannibal Corpse's 'Tomb of the Mutilated' (1992)|url=http://www.tombofthemutilated.net/Cannibal-Corpse-Tomb-Of-The-Mutilated-Review.html|publisher=tombofthemutilated.net|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013080058/http://www.tombofthemutilated.net/Cannibal-Corpse-Tomb-Of-The-Mutilated-Review.html|accessdate=February 6, 2009|archivedate=October 13, 2007}}</ref> * [[CKY (band)|CKY]] – ''[[Volume 1 (CKY album)|Volume 1]]'' (1999) ** The cover originally depicted a stylized cartoon depiction of [[R. Budd Dwyer]]'s live television suicide. After many complaints of offensiveness, the label forced the band to replace the offensive cover with a black and white cut-out of one of the band's live performances. The album was released with the band's original name Camp Kill Yourself, which was switched to CKY.<ref name="dwyer">{{cite news |url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/music/future-shock-she-wants-revenge-the-donnas-cky-and-more-6595143 |title=Future Shock: She Wants Revenge, The Donnas, CKY, And More |last=Leatherman |first=Benjamin |publisher=''[[Phoenix New Times]]'' |date=August 17, 2007 |accessdate=May 19, 2018 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180519204543/http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/music/future-shock-she-wants-revenge-the-donnas-cky-and-more-6595143 |archivedate=May 19, 2018 |df= }}</ref> * [[The Coup]] – ''[[Party Music]]'' (2001) ** The original cover art, designed in June 2001, depicted Boots Riley and Pam the Funkstress destroying the [[Twin Towers (NYC)|Twin Towers]] of the [[World Trade Center (1973–2001)|World Trade Center]]. After the [[September 11 attacks]], the group postponed the album's release until November of that year, with the record now sporting an alternate cover depicting a hand holding a flaming martini glass.<ref name="TS">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestranger.com/seattle/Content?oid=8708 |title=The Coup's Bomb |last=Goedde |first=Brian |publisher=''The Stranger'' |date=August 17, 2007 |accessdate=May 19, 2018 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911223817/http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/Content?oid=8708 |archivedate=September 11, 2014 |df= }}</ref> * [[Green Day]] – ''[[Kerplunk (album)|Kerplunk]]'' (1992) ** The cover features a white picture (with some green added in) of a teenage girl wearing a flower shirt holding a smoking gun. The back cover features a boy lying on the ground with a gunshot wound on his back. Retail stores such as [[Walmart]] and [[Kmart]] initially refused to carry ''Kerplunk''. The band saw continued controversy on their next album ''[[Dookie]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2016/10/ranking-every-green-day-album-from-worst-to-best/full-post/ |title=Ranking: Every Green Day Album from Worst to Best |date=2016-10-07 |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |language=English |access-date=2017-07-13 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216201122/https://consequenceofsound.net/2016/10/ranking-every-green-day-album-from-worst-to-best/full-post/ |archivedate=2017-12-16 |df= }}</ref> * [[Green Day]] – ''[[Dookie]]'' (1994) ** The cover art shows an animated picture of dogs throwing bombs and dirt on people and buildings and a huge explosion with the band's name on top of the cloud. A blimp on the left in the sky says "Bad Year" (possibly a parody of the [[Goodyear Blimp]]) and on the right is a man with a harp in a cloud. Retailers [[Walmart]] and [[Kmart]] refused to sell the album because of this. Despite the controversy, no alternative cover has existed.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}} However, later printings of the album edited the back cover for copyright reasons, airbrushing out a puppet of [[Ernie (Sesame Street)|Ernie]] from ''[[Sesame Street]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.feelnumb.com/2011/03/31/ernie-from-sesame-street-had-to-be-airbrushed-off-the-back-cover-of-the-green-day-album-dookie/|title=Ernie From Sesame Street Had To Be Airbrushed Off The Back Cover Of The Green Day Album “Dookie”|date=31 March 2011|publisher=|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717214105/http://www.feelnumb.com/2011/03/31/ernie-from-sesame-street-had-to-be-airbrushed-off-the-back-cover-of-the-green-day-album-dookie/|archivedate=17 July 2015|df=}}</ref> * [[Ice-T]] – ''[[Home Invasion (album)|Home Invasion]]'' (1993) ** The album's cover depicted a white boy listening to rap music in the midst of a home invasion in which Blacks are attacking Whites (presumably the boy's parents). [[Sire Records]], owned by [[Time Warner]], refused to release the album with the cover, and Ice-T left the label as a result.<ref>''The Ice Opinion'', Ice-T as dictated to Heidi Siegmund, St. Martin's Press, New York, 1994</ref> * [[Lynyrd Skynyrd]] – ''[[Street Survivors]]'' (1977) ** The original cover sleeve for ''Street Survivors'' had featured a photograph of the band, particularly Steve Gaines, standing in the street of a town engulfed in flames. Three days after the album was released, three of the band members were killed in a plane crash due to fuel exhaustion. Out of respect for the deceased (and at the request of Teresa Gaines, Steve Gaines' widow), MCA Records withdrew the original cover and replaced it with a similar image of the band against a simple black background. Thirty years later, for the deluxe CD version of Street Survivors, the original "flames" cover was restored.<ref name=Check-Six>{{cite web |title=The 'Lynyrd Skynyrd' Crash |url=http://www.check-six.com/Crash_Sites/LynyrdSkynyrd-N55VM.htm |work=Check-Six.com |date=May 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2008 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AxpnRuHV?url=http://www.check-six.com/Crash_Sites/LynyrdSkynyrd-N55VM.htm |archivedate=September 26, 2012 |df= }}</ref> * [[Manic Street Preachers]] – ''[[Journal for Plague Lovers]]'' (2009) ** The album art depicts a painting by [[Jenny Saville]]. A number of UK supermarkets deemed the red/[[ochre]] colours on the portrait to be blood, and therefore used alternative packaging to stock the item.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/may/15/manic-street-preachers-album-supermarkets Manic Street Preachers album cover censored by supermarkets] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420234758/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/may/15/manic-street-preachers-album-supermarkets |date=2017-04-20 }} The Guardian, 15 May 2009</ref> The alternative packaging in question is a [[longbox]], a type of outer packaging used for some CDs in the 1980s and early to mid-1990s. * [[Metallica]] – ''[[Kill 'Em All]]'' (1983) ** The album was originally set to be titled ''Metal Up Your Ass'', with the cover featuring a toilet bowl with a hand clutching a dagger emerging from it. However, at the request of [[Megaforce Records]] (who thought the original album title would be inappropriate),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.encycmet.com/biography/ |title=ENCYCLOPEDIA METALLICA – Complete history |publisher=Encycmet.com |date=September 3, 1983 |accessdate=June 21, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710070554/http://www.encycmet.com/biography/ |archivedate=July 10, 2013 |df= }}</ref> the band changed the album title to ''Kill 'Em All''. They also changed the artwork, this time depicting a shadow of a hand releasing a bloodied hammer. * [[The Offspring]] – ''[[The Offspring (album)|The Offspring]]'' (1989) ** The album's original artwork depicted an image of a man's body exploding as the [[Alien (creature in Alien franchise)|xenomorph]] from the ''[[Alien (franchise)|Alien]]'' franchise holding a [[Fender Stratocaster|Stratocaster]] guitar emerges from his chest. The album was reportedly banned for being "too grotesque",<ref name="Barker"/> and on the 1995 reissue, the artwork was replaced by a blurry black-and-white picture of a man. It was later admitted that the band and their studio never really liked the original artwork. * [[Pink Floyd]] – ''[[Wish You Were Here (Pink Floyd album)|Wish You Were Here]]'' (1975) ** The artwork depicts two men shaking hands in an alley at [[Warner Bros. Studios]], with one on fire. As some retailers deemed it "too violent" and refused the sell the album, the cover was replaced on some re-releases with a black background featuring the album's four-elements sticker.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/goodlife/11574460/10-banned-album-covers.html?frame=3287295|title=10 Banned Album Covers|first=Rachel|last=Thompson|work=The Telegraph|date=1 May 2015|accessdate=24 June 2015|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626155420/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/goodlife/11574460/10-banned-album-covers.html?frame=3287295|archivedate=26 June 2015|df=}}</ref>
==Other reasons== <!--IMPORTANT! If you add an album without providing a reference or providing an explanation for why or how its album cover is "controversial", THE ALBUM WILL BE REMOVED! See discussion page.--> * [[The Mamas and the Papas]] – ''[[If You Can Believe Your Eyes and Ears]]'' (1966) ** The album cover, which features the four members in a bathtub, also featured a toilet in the far right corner. The inclusion of this toilet was controversial for the time and copies with the cover were pulled due to complaints of indecency. The copies were re-issued with a text-box pasted on top of the toilet. Later issues of the album feature both the toilet and the bathtub cropped out entirely.<ref name="stonelist">{{cite web|last1=Edwards|first1=Gavin|title=Banned in the U.S.A.: 20 Wildest Censored Album Covers|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/banned-in-the-u-s-a-20-wildest-censored-album-covers-20150115|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=4 October 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930142116/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/banned-in-the-u-s-a-20-wildest-censored-album-covers-20150115|archivedate=30 September 2016|df=}}</ref> * [[The Rolling Stones]] – ''[[Beggars Banquet]]'' (1968) ** The original album cover featured a toilet wall which had been defaced. Mick Jagger and Keith Richards defaced the toilet wall themselves. The album cover was rejected by Decca, and kept out of shops until a new album cover was designed <ref>[http://www.nme.com/photos/the-rolling-stones-album-artwork-secrets-revealed-the-story-behind-every-sleeve-1416155]</ref>. * [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] – ''[[In Utero (album)|In Utero]]'' (1993) ** When ''In Utero'' was released, there were many objections to the song "[[Rape Me]]", despite the band's claims that the lyrics were "anti-rape." Retailers [[Wal-Mart]] and [[Kmart]] refused to sell the album because of the back cover artwork (featuring model fetuses), so a "clean" version was released for them which featured an altered version of the back cover and listed the title "Rape Me" as "Waif Me", though the song remained unchanged.<ref>[http://www.nirvanaclub.com/get.php?section=info/general&file=nfc_faq2.htm#96 Nirvana fan club FAQ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107055629/http://www.nirvanaclub.com/get.php?section=info%2Fgeneral&file=nfc_faq2.htm |date=2017-11-07 }} Retrieved on 10 June 2006</ref><ref>[http://ericnuzum.com/banned/incidents/90s.html Banned albums of the 90s] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070621101224/http://ericnuzum.com/banned/incidents/90s.html |date=2007-06-21 }} Retrieved on 10 June 2006</ref> The band acquiesced to the demands to change the artwork because members [[Kurt Cobain]] and [[Krist Novoselic]] were only able to buy music from the two chain stores as children; as a result they wanted to "make their music available to kids who don't have the opportunity to go to mom-and-pop stores".<ref>Gordinier, Jeff. "[http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,301746,00.html Attention Kmart Shoppers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214110010/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,301746,00.html |date=2009-02-14 }}". ''Entertainment Weekly''. April 8, 1994. Retrieved January 20, 2009.</ref> * [[Van Halen]] – ''[[Balance (Van Halen album)|Balance]]'' (1995) ** The cover in most markets features two nude conjoined twins sitting on a teeter-totter. The cover was altered in some markets, including Japan, to remove one of the twins entirely from the photograph.<ref name="stonelist"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glenwexlerstudio.com/files/Resource_Balance.pdf|work=RESOURCEMAGONLINE.com|title=Van Halen: Balance|format=PDF|accessdate=October 30, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150815113325/http://www.glenwexlerstudio.com/files/Resource_Balance.pdf|archivedate=August 15, 2015|df=}}</ref> * [[Arctic Monkeys]] – ''[[Whatever People Say I Am, That's What I'm Not]]'' (2006) ** The cover sleeve showing Chris McClure, a friend of the band, smoking a cigarette, was criticised by the head of the [[National Health Service|NHS]] in [[Scotland]] for "reinforcing the idea that smoking is OK".<ref name="smoking">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4677356.stm BBC News:Arctic Monkeys defend album cover] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081225201050/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4677356.stm |date=2008-12-25 }} Retrieved on 5 June 2006</ref> The image on the CD itself is a shot of an ashtray full of cigarettes. The band's product manager denied the accusation, and in fact suggested the opposite — "You can see from the image smoking is not doing him the world of good".<ref name="smoking"/> * [[Pusha T]] – ''[[Daytona (album)|Daytona]]'' (2018) ** The cover depicts a picture of deceased singer [[Whitney Houston]]'s bathroom showing drugs that were used by her. It was bought by [[Kanye West]] for $85,000. Houston's family stated they found the artwork "disgusting and disrespectful".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/pusha-t-daytona-album-artwork-whitney-houston/|title=Whitney Houston’s Family Calls For Pusha T’s Album Art To Be Changed|publisher=Highsnobiety|accessdate=May 31, 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180527143513/https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/pusha-t-daytona-album-artwork-whitney-houston/|archivedate=May 27, 2018|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/GMA/Culture/kanye-west-paid-85k-controversial-whitney-houston-photo/story?id=55433834|title=Kanye West uses controversial photo reportedly linked to Whitney Houston for Pusha T's album cover|publisher=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=May 31, 2018}]</ref>
